description:
When your son is born, you will know a gripping, powerful love. And, looking into his little face, you will believe that he could someday change the world, perhaps even save it. Then you will learn the heart-wrenching horror when you learn that he is sick ? barely clinging to life. That's when every moment you have with him is precious. That's when you either pray for the gods to intervene or you curse them for torturing you. Curse or prayer, the gods will deliver an answer. Your son will live ? as something more than a man. Forbidden to touch as a killing tool, he has become the most dangerous weapon ever created. You only want the best for him. Yet all he thinks about is why he can't play at war with the other boys. Hammer of the Gods is an epic tapestry woven from the threads of Viking myth and powerful modern storytelling. And since it comes from the creative minds of Mike Oeming (Powers) and Mark Wheatly (Breathtaker), this epic doesn't completely take itself seriously. This first issue is one of four that will tell the story of Modi, the boy who is the Hammer of the Gods. Featuring a beautiful cover by Frank Cho.

As the baby Modi lies dying, his distraught parents beg the Gods to intervene. They do, with a Valkyrie named Skogul ensuring not only his survival, but also bestowing a blessing of prodigious strength and great wisdom.

It comes with a warning, though: Should Modi raise a weapon his soul will be forfeit. Despite his gifts the adult Modi becomes disillusioned with the Gods, and swears to destroy them.
name: Hammer of the Gods

description: With the loss of his parents still a fresh wound in his soul, Modi sets off to claim revenge on the Gods. Along the way, he's gong to face corrupt Valkyries, dragons, witches, and undead soldiers. Living in the age of Beowulf was no walk in the park! For Modi, this is his test. If he can overcome these barriers to his revenge, then he will know that even gods might learn to feat him. And if that's not enough, get ready for Modi's hand-to-hand battle with the sexy Valkyrie known as Skogul! This solid, high-energy fun from the artist and co-creator of Powers even offers an important life lesson: walk softly and carry a big rock!
name: Entrance to Valhalla

description: It took an extra issue, but all your questions are answered here. Every battle will be fought! Thorr and the Gods of Asgard face down the Giants in a bloody blow-down that lasts for weeks! But will Modi survive? Will Loki offer help or harm? Will you love the great cover by Dave Johnson? Of course you will!
name: Hammer of the Gods

description: Modi and the fallen Valkyrie, Skgul, arrive in Valhalla to find the gods crying into their beer! The shame of it all! The Gods are a bunch of wussies! So Modi immediately starts kicking some Asgard! This is a five-star-smackdown as Thorr and the Gods face the fighting vigor of two exceptional mortals! And all the while, as the conflict between Modi and the Gods rages on, the Giants tear at the walls of Valhalla, ripping it apart stone by stone!
name: The Final Battle

description: December 7, 1974. Reprints a Planet of the Apes adventure, "The Defence." Script by Doug Moench, pencils by George Tuska, inks by Mike Esposito. Includes three back-up stories featuring Gulliar Jones Warrior of Mars (by George Alec Effinger and Gray Morrow) and Ka-Zar (by Gerry Conway, Barry Windsor-Smith, and Bill Everett).

First appearance of Apeslayer, using modified Killraven strips from Amazing Adventures with the Martians redrawn as Apes, in order to fill issues as the UK reprints were catching up with the US Planet of the Apes comic.
